<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Chiang Mai to Chiang Rai via Doi Mae Salong</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Chiang Mai to Chiang Rai via Doi Mae Salong</h2><p><i>Northern Thailand · Chiang Mai to Chiang Rai via Fang and Mae Salong</i></p><p><b>Tea-terrace mountain villages settled by Yunnanese Kuomintang refugees, the Mekong's Golden Triangle, hot springs.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>304 km (189 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>Full day; ideally 2 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>November–February (cool, clear, cherry blossoms in late Jan)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Steep and twisting from Tha Ton to Mae Salong; burning-season smoke (Mar–Apr); border zones near Myanmar require permission off the main road</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>613</td></tr></table><hr><p>An alternative way from Chiang Mai to Chiang Rai that skips the highway entirely. The road leaves the main valley at Chiang Dao (its limestone massif rises 2,225 m sharp out of rice fields), crosses through Fang's hot-springs basin to Tha Ton on the Kok River, then climbs to Doi Mae Salong (1,800 m) — a Yunnanese Kuomintang refugee village settled in 1961 by Chinese Nationalist soldiers who fled Yunnan after Mao's victory and ended up serving as anti-communist auxiliaries on the Thai-Burma border. They turned to tea growing in the 1980s when the opium trade was suppressed. The village still feels Chinese — Mandarin signs, tea-tasting houses, Yunnanese noodles. The drive ends near the Mekong at the Golden Triangle, where Thailand, Laos, and Myanmar meet.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Chiang Dao</b> — The 2,225 m Doi Chiang Dao limestone massif drops sharply from rice fields. Chiang Dao Cave runs 5+ km into the mountain — the first 360 m is well-developed with Buddha images; deeper sections need a guide with a lantern.</li><li><b>Tha Ton</b> — River town on the Kok. Long-tail boats run downstream to Chiang Rai (4 hrs) — a quietly beautiful slow trip past hill-tribe villages. Wat Tha Ton's hilltop terraces have nine temples on ascending levels.</li><li><b>Doi Mae Salong</b> — 1,800 m village built by Kuomintang 93rd Division refugees in 1961. Yunnanese architecture, Chinese cemeteries, tea terraces. Best visited late January for cherry blossoms (sakura). The Chinese Martyrs Memorial Hall tells the strange political story.</li><li><b>Mae Sai</b> — Thailand's northernmost town and a road border with Myanmar's Tachileik. The 2018 Tham Luang cave rescue happened in the hills 60 km southwest.</li><li><b>Golden Triangle</b> — Confluence of the Ruak and Mekong rivers — Thailand on the south bank, Myanmar to the west, Laos to the east. The Hall of Opium museum tells the unsanitized history of the trade that financed half the region for 200 years.</li><li><b>Chiang Rai / Wat Rong Khun</b> — The 'White Temple' (1997, ongoing) is artist Chalermchai Kositpipat's surreal vision of Buddhist iconography — bone-white plaster, mirror inlays, demon-clawed bridges. Free entry.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
